  "prompt": "What is dyarchy and when was it introduced in India?",
  "response": "Dyarchy is a system of governance that was introduced in India under the Government of India Act 1919. It referred to a dual system of government where certain subjects were allocated to elected representatives (the \"provincial\" or local government) while others remained under the control of the British government (the \"reserved\" subjects). \n\nThis system was implemented in the provinces of British India in an effort to increase Indian participation in governance while still maintaining British control over key functions of government. Under dyarchy, the elected Indian ministers were responsible for the administration of subjects that they controlled, but their powers were limited and were checked by the British officials who oversaw the reserved subjects. \n\nThe dyarchic system was intended as a step toward greater self-governance, but it faced criticism for its limited scope and the continuing dominance of British officials over significant areas of governance. The dyarchy system was ultimately replaced by the Government of India Act 1935, which provided for a more comprehensive scheme of provincial autonomy while still retaining substantial central control.",
